particularly around session ending and the \\\"split commits after session end\\\" problem:\\n\\n## Current Session End Detection\\n\\nThe session becomes `ENDED` via two paths:\\n1. **Agent fires `SessionStop` hook** → `markSessionEnded()` in `lifecycle.go:675` sets `Phase=ended`, `EndedAt=now`\\n2. **Stale detection** → `IsStale()` in `state.go:231` — sessions with no interaction for 7 days are auto-deleted on next Load\\n\\n## The Split Commit Problem\\n\\nHere's the core tension:\\n\\n1. Agent does work, touching files A, B, C\\n2. Session ends (agent closes) → phase becomes `ENDED`\\n3. User commits files A, B → PostCommit condenses, marks carry-forward with file C\\n4. User commits file C later → PostCommit needs to associate this with the session too\\n\\nTo support step 4, the system currently:\\n- Keeps the `ENDED` session state file around (with `FilesTouched: [C]`)\\n- Keeps a shadow branch (carry-forward creates a new one at `carryForwardToNewShadowBranch`)\\n- Only sets `FullyCondensed=true` when ALL carry-forward files are gone (`manual_commit_hooks.go:995-996`)\\n- Only deletes the state file via the 7-day stale threshold\\n\\n## The Problems I See\\n\\n### 1. Shadow branches linger indefinitely for ENDED sessions with carry-forward\\n\\nWhen PostCommit condenses an ENDED session but carry-forward files remain (`manual_commit_hooks.go:980-982`), a new shadow branch is created. This branch persists until either:\\n- The next commit includes those carry-forward files, OR  \\n- 7 days pass and `IsStale()` deletes the state → `listAllSessionStates` cleans up the orphaned state, but the **shadow branch itself is NOT cleaned up** (only listed as orphaned by `ListOrphanedItems`)\\n\\nIf the user never commits those carry-forward files (reverts them, or stages different files), the shadow branch hangs around forever.\\n\\n### 2. `ENDED` sessions participate in every PostCommit unnecessarily\\n\\nIn `PostCommit` (`manual_commit_hooks.go:808-817`), every session on the worktree is iterated. ENDED sessions with `FullyCondensed=false` go through the full `postCommitProcessSession` path on every commit, even if the committed files have zero overlap with the session's files. The `shouldCondenseWithOverlapCheck` does gate this, but the overhead of resolving shadow branches, checking content, etc. runs on every commit.\\n\\n### 3. No explicit \\\"session has nothing left to give\\\" detection\\n\\nThe only terminal state for a session is `FullyCondensed=true` (set at `manual_commit_hooks.go:995-996`). But this requires the carry-forward files to actually be committed. If a user:\\n- Reverts agent changes (`git checkout -- file.txt`)\\n- Manually edits the file to something completely different\\n- Never commits those specific files\\n\\n...the ENDED session lingers with stale `FilesTouched` until the 7-day timeout.\\n\\n### 4. The `activeSessionInteractionThreshold` is a blunt instrument\\n\\nAt `manual_commit_hooks.go:701`, ACTIVE sessions older than 24h fall through to the overlap check. This means a killed agent (no Stop hook) eventually stops being auto-condensed, but it takes 24 hours. During that window, every commit from ANY source gets condensed into the stale session.\\n\\n## Proposal: Content-Based Session Completion\\n\\nInstead of relying on time-based heuristics and shadow branch presence, we could add a **content-based check** at PostCommit that detects when an ENDED session's carry-forward files no longer have agent content:\\n\\n### Option A: Detect reverted carry-forward files in PostCommit\\n\\nIn `postCommitProcessSession`, after the carry-forward computation (`manual_commit_hooks.go:966-989`), add a check:\\n\\n```\\nIf session is ENDED and has carry-forward files:\\n  For each carry-forward file, compare working tree content against HEAD\\n  If the file in working tree matches HEAD (user committed/reverted it already)\\n    OR the file doesn't exist in the working tree anymore\\n    → Remove from carry-forward list\\n  If carry-forward list becomes empty → set FullyCondensed=true\\n```\\n\\nThis would happen even when the committed files DON'T overlap with carry-forward, catching reverts/deletions. But it adds working-tree reads on every commit for ENDED sessions.\\n\\n### Option B: Move association from shadow branches to session state\\n\\nThe shadow branch currently serves two purposes:\\n1. **Storage**: Holds the transcript and checkpoint metadata before condensation\\n2. **Association**: Used by content-overlap checks to match committed files to sessions\\n\\nAfter condensation, purpose 1 is served by `entire/checkpoints/v1`. Purpose 2 only matters for carry-forward.\\n\\nWe could **store carry-forward file hashes directly in the session state** instead of maintaining a shadow branch:\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"carry_forward_files\\\": {\\n    \\\"src/auth.go\\\": \\\"sha256:abc123...\\\",\\n    \\\"src/main.go\\\": \\\"sha256:def456...\\\"\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThen PostCommit could:\\n1. Check if any committed files are in `carry_forward_files`\\n2. Compare by content hash (did the committed content match what the agent wrote?)\\n3. Remove matched files from carry-forward\\n4. No shadow branch needed for ENDED sessions\\n\\nThis would:\\n- Eliminate shadow branches for ENDED sessions entirely\\n- Make carry-forward self-contained in the state file\\n- Allow immediate cleanup of reverted files (hash won't match)\\n- Reduce git ref clutter\\n\\n### Option C: Time-bounded carry-forward with user opt-in\\n\\nSet a much shorter timeout for ENDED session carry-forward (e.g., 1 hour instead of 7 days). After that timeout, auto-cleanup the session and shadow branch. If the user wants to split commits across a longer period, they could use `entire link` to explicitly associate a commit.\\n\\nThis is simpler but loses the automatic association.\\n\\n---\\n\\n**My recommendation**: Option B is the cleanest — it decouples association from shadow branches, makes the state fully self-contained, and naturally handles reverts. It's also the most testable (pure state-file operations vs. git branch management).\\n\\nWant me to dig deeper into any of these options, or should I start prototyping Option B?\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":1228,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":86076,\"output_tokens\":1565,\"server_tool_use\":{\"web_search_requests\":0,\"web_fetch_requests\":0},\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":1228,\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0},\"inference_geo\":\"\",\"iterations\":[],\"speed\":\"standard\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYkbFivEwD3pra5MUVRTa\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"fbba239c-88bb-4ce1-97ef-fad6d5fb6f00\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T20:49:35.747Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"fbba239c-88bb-4ce1-97ef-fad6d5fb6f00\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"Stop\",\"hookName\":\"Stop\",\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code stop\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"50949ada-a4ff-4490-9093-a83335d4601a\",\"toolUseID\":\"50949ada-a4ff-4490-9093-a83335d4601a\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T20:49:35.856Z\",\"uuid\":\"de16d40a-2810-473c-b272-76e1bc66b76a\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"de16d40a-2810-473c-b272-76e1bc66b76a\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"type\":\"system\",\"subtype\":\"stop_hook_summary\",\"hookCount\":1,\"hookInfos\":[{\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code stop\",\"durationMs\":800}