age\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01RVq6PTmHL7naLkg9pECE2R\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"\\n\\nGreat question. You're right — in the current flow, when the user splits commits:\\n\\n1. **Commit 1** (files A, B): condenses session → writes transcript + metadata to `entire/checkpoints/v1` → deletes shadow branch → carry-forward keeps file C\\n2. **Commit 2** (file C): needs to condense again with the **same transcript** — but the shadow branch is gone\\n\\nCurrently `carryForwardToNewShadowBranch` creates a **new** shadow branch at the new HEAD specifically for this — it copies the remaining files so `CondenseSession` can still extract transcript data from it for commit 2.\\n\\nSo the question is: with Option B (no shadow branch for ENDED sessions), where does commit 2 get the transcript?\\n\\nThe answer is: **it doesn't need the shadow branch for the transcript**. Look at `CondenseSession` (`manual_commit_condensation.go:124-142`):\\n\\n```go\\nif hasShadowBranch {\\n    sessionData, extractErr = s.extractSessionData(...)\\n} else {\\n    // Falls back to live transcript\\n    sessionData, extractErr = s.extractSessionDataFromLiveTranscript(ctx, state)\\n}\\n```\\n\\nFor an ENDED session on commit 2, the live transcript file is still on disk (the code explicitly notes at `lifecycle.go:444-447` that transcripts aren't cleaned up for this reason). But there's a subtlety — `extractSessionDataFromLiveTranscript` reads from `state.TranscriptPath`, which points to the agent's transcript file. For Claude Code that's `~/.claude/projects/.../session.jsonl`. That file persists after the session ends.\\n\\n**However**, there are two real gaps:\\n\\n1. **Transcript scoping**: After commit 1, `CheckpointTranscriptStart` is updated to `result.TotalTranscriptLines` (the full transcript length). On commit 2, `sessionHasNewContent` would see `transcriptLines <= CheckpointTranscriptStart` and report **no new content**. The carry-forward currently works around this because `carryForwardToNewShadowBranch` resets `CheckpointTranscriptStart = 0` — so the full transcript gets re-read. Without the shadow branch, we'd need to preserve this reset behavior.\\n\\n2. **Prompt data**: The shadow branch stores `prompt.txt`. Without it, the carry-forward commit would need to get prompts from either the filesystem (`readPromptsFromFilesystem`) or from the already-condensed checkpoint on `entire/checkpoints/v1`.\\n\\nSo Option B works, but the carry-forward state needs to include a bit more than just file hashes:\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"carry_forward\\\": {\\n    \\\"files\\\": {\\n      \\\"src/auth.go\\\": \\\"sha256:abc123...\\\",\\n      \\\"src/main.go\\\": \\\"sha256:def456...\\\"\\n    },\\n    \\\"transcript_start\\\": 0,\\n    \\\"source_checkpoint_id\\\": \\\"a3b2c4d5e6f7\\\"\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nWhere `source_checkpoint_id` lets commit 2 **read the transcript from the already-condensed checkpoint** on `entire/checkpoints/v1` rather than needing a shadow branch at all. The flow would be:\\n\\n1. **Commit 1**: Condenses normally (shadow branch or live transcript) → writes to `entire/checkpoints/v1` → detects carry-forward files → stores file hashes + `source_checkpoint_id` in session state → deletes shadow branch\\n2. **Commit 2**: Sees ENDED session with carry-forward → committed files overlap with carry-forward hashes → reads transcript from `entire/checkpoints/v1` using `source_checkpoint_id` → writes new checkpoint with same transcript → clears carry-forward → `FullyCondensed=true`\\n\\nThis way the transcript is read from permanent storage, not a shadow branch. The shadow branch becomes truly ephemeral — only needed during the active session, deleted at first commit.\\n\\nThe one edge case is if `entire/checkpoints/v1` doesn't exist yet (first ever commit) — but that can't happen because carry-forward only exists after a successful condensation which creates the branch.\\n