"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01KVmsZJGgkoPym9YJr7Lstq\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"The user wants to think about this more fundamentally. Let me think about what we actually need and what git primitives are available.\\n\\nThe core requirements:\\n1. Store a snapshot of \\\"what the agent wrote\\\" for each file\\n2. Keep it around until all those files are committed (possibly across multiple split commits)\\n3. Be able to compare committed content against this snapshot (both hash equality and content reads)\\n4. Don't pollute the branch namespace\\n5. Don't get GC'd\\n\\nLet me think about git primitives:\\n\\n**Git refs that prevent GC:**\\n- Branches (`refs/heads/`) — current approach, visible in `git branch`\\n\\n\\n- Tags (`refs/tags/`) — visible in `git tag`, same problem\\n- Notes (`refs/notes/`) — attached to commits, less visible\\n- Custom refs (`refs/entire/...`) — arbitrary namespace, not shown by default in `git branch`\\n- `refs/stash` — special, probably not appropriate\\n- `keep` files in `.git/objects/pack/` — too low level\\n\\nWait — **custom ref namespaces** are the key here. Git allows arbitrary refs under any path. `refs/heads/` is branches, `refs/tags/` is tags, but I could use something like `refs/entire/snapshots/...` as a valid ref that keeps objects alive without cluttering the visible branch or tag namespace.\\n\\nThis approach is similar to how GitHub stores PR refs under `refs/pull/` or how Gerrit uses `refs/changes/`. It's essentially what I'm already doing with shadow branches under `refs/heads/entire/...`, but moved to a separate namespace so they don't pollute `git branch` output. The real problem though — lingering refs from ended sessions — still persists regardless of where I store them.\\n\\nNow I'm considering git notes as an alternative, where I could attach a note to HEAD containing the agent's file snapshot hashes. content. Notes are stored as blob objects referenced by a note ref. But notes are per-commit, and we need per-session state that spans commits.\\n\\n2. **Annotated tags** — Could create lightweight tags for snapshots. Same visibility issue as branches though.\\n\\n3. **Store blobs in the metadata branch tree** — Instead of a separate shadow branch, store the agent's file snapshots as part of the `entire/checkpoints/v1` tree. When condensing, alongside the transcript, also store the file blobs. Then carry-forward just references those blobs from the already-committed tree.\\n\\n4. **Loose object pinning** — Create a ref that points to a tree object containing the agent's files. Could use `refs/entire/snapshots/<session-id>`. Lightweight, targeted, auto-cleaned.\\n\\n5. **Working tree approach** — Keep copies of the agent-written files on the filesystem instead of storing them in git, like `.entire/snapshots/<session-id>/`. This sidesteps git ref issues but trades off disk space and loses deduplication.\\n\\n6. **Git index / staging area trick** — Not really applicable.\\n\\n7. **Completely different model: don't store snapshots, use diffs instead** — Store the patch the agent produced rather than full file content, then apply it during carry-forward to see what remains. The downside is patches break easily when users edit files.\\n\\n8. **Deferred condensation model** — Record which commits were active during a session and handle the metadata association later (at push time or on demand) instead of at commit time. This eliminates the need for shadow branches during active work.\\n\\n9. **Embed**\\n\\nI'm realizing the core tension: the shadow branch handles two separate concerns. During an active session, it buffers checkpoints before the user commits anything. After the first commit, it stores a reference snapshot for comparing subsequent commits. Git notes could work for metadata but don't solve the session-scoping problem, and I'm wondering if the reference snapshot really needs to live in git