arbage collection. On each commit, I'd compare what's been committed against the stored hashes, and when everything's accounted for, I'd rebuild the tree without that entry. This keeps the mechanism simple—one ref total across all sessions instead of one per session—and the cleanup happens naturally as files get committed or reverted.\\n\\nActually, I'm wondering if I should just embed this whole thing back into the checkpoint structure...\\n\\nInstead of maintaining a separate keep-alive mechanism, I could store a snapshot subtree directly in the checkpoint metadata that captures the agent's file state at that moment. This snapshot stays reachable forever through the metadata branch and serves as a permanent record of what the agent intended to write. When checking for remaining changes, I'd read from this snapshot instead of the shadow branch. The snapshot is small relative to transcripts and doesn't need cleanup—it's just historical data. This approach eliminates the need for extra refs entirely and keeps everything self-contained within the checkpoint structure.\\n\\nThe tradeoff is that file content gets added to the metadata branch, which increases its size, but since these are git blobs and the same content already exists in the user's commit, git's object deduplication means there's no actual extra storage cost.\\n\\nFor carry-forward logic, I'm comparing the committed file hash against the shadow file hash — if they match, nothing needs to carry forward. When they differ, the shadow blob is a separate object that needs to stay reachable, and storing it in the checkpoint snapshot keeps it accessible via the checkpoints branch without duplicating storage.\\n\\nI'm leaning toward a hybrid approach: use a ref in the `refs/entire/` namespace for the active session shadow, which keeps the branch listing clean while still maintaining the shadow state.\\n\\nAt condensation time, I'd write the agent's file snapshots directly into the checkpoint, then delete the shadow ref. For carry-forward, I'd read those blobs back from the checkpoint snapshot without needing the shadow branch anymore. Session cleanup becomes simpler since the checkpoint data persists and the shadow ref is already gone.\\n\\nLet me think through some other creative approaches the user might find interesting — git replace refs, grafts, worktrees for storage — though most of these are either deprecated or not quite suited to the problem.\\n\\nThe most practical options boil down to using a `refs/entire/` namespace to keep things organized without cluttering the branch view, or embedding snapshots directly in the checkpoint structure itself.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":495,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":106659,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":495},\"output_tokens\":9,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYkdSxMR1NRVG83yfMLcs\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"39612056-a222-4310-9417-5ac22442121e\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:18:59.537Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"39612056-a222-4310-9417-5ac22442121e\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01KVmsZJGgkoPym9YJr7Lstq\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Good — let me think about this from scratch. The actual requirements are:\\n\\n1. Store \\\"what the agent wrote\\\" per file (blobs)\\n2. Keep blobs alive (no GC) until carry-forward completes\\n3. Compare committed content against them (hash + sometimes content reads)\\n4. Clean up naturally when done\\n\\nHere are the git primitives and other approaches worth considering:\\n\\n## 1. Custom ref namespace (`refs/entire/`)\\n\\nGit refs are just files in `.git/refs/`. Only `refs/heads/` shows in `git branch`, only `refs/tags/` in `git tag`. But `refs/entire/snapshots/<session-id>` is a perfectly valid ref that:\\n- Keeps objects reachable (prevents GC)\\n- Is invisible to `git branch`, `git tag`\\n- Can be enumerated with `git for-each-ref refs/entire/`\\n- Can be selectively pushed or excluded\\n\\nThis is how GitHub stores PR heads (`refs/pull/123/head`), Gerrit stores changesets (`refs/changes/`), etc.\\n\\nBut this is mostly cosmetic — it's the same approach as today, just in a different namespace. The lingering-ref-for-ENDED-sessions problem is identical.\\n\\n## 2. Embed snapshots in `entire/checkpoints/v1`\\n\\nAt condensation time, write the agent's file blobs **into the checkpoint tree** alongside the transcript:\\n\\n```\\na3/b2c4d5e6f7/\\n├── metadata.json\\n├── 0/\\n│   ├── full.jsonl\\n│   └── prompt.txt\\n└── snapshot/           ← agent's file state\\n    ├── src/auth.go\\n    └── src/main.go\\n```\\n\\nSince `entire/checkpoints/v1` is a permanent ref, these blobs are always reachable. No shadow branch needed after the first commit. Carry-forward reads from this snapshot tree.\\n\\n**Key insight**: git deduplicates at the blob level. If the agent wrote exactly what ended up in the user's commit, the blob already exists — zero extra storage. Only genuinely different content (the carry-forward case) adds bytes, and those blobs are small relative to transcripts.\\n\\nThis gives you the \\\"staging area\\\" semantics: the snapshot is \\\"what the agent intended\\\", and each user commit chips away at it until `snapshot/ matches HEAD` for all files.\\n\\n## 3. Filesystem snapshots (`.entire/snapshots/`)\\n\\nSkip git entirely for this. When the session produces files, copy them to `.entire/snapshots/<session-id>/src/auth.go`. Compare against these copies on each commit.\\n\\n- No GC issues (it's just files)\\n- No git refs at all\\n- Simple to reason about\\n- Downside: not deduplicated, uses real disk space, needs gitignore rules\\n- Downside: not portable across machines (but neither is the current shadow branch)\\n\\n## 4. Single accumulator ref\\n\\nInstead of one ref per session, maintain a single `refs/entire/keep` (or a tree object on `entire/checkpoints/v1`) that accumulates all carry-forward blobs from all sessions:\\n\\n```\\nrefs/entire/keep → tree:\\n  <session-id-1>/src/auth.go → blob\\n  <session-id-2>/main.py → blob\\n```\\n\\nOne ref, all sessions. When a session's carry-forward completes, rebuild the tree without its entries. When the last session completes, the ref can be deleted.\\n\\n## 5. `git notes` on user commits\\n\\nAttach a note to the user's commit containing the snapshot tree hash:\\n\\n```\\ngit notes --ref=entire add -m \\\"<tree-hash>\\\" <commit>\\n```\\n\\nNotes are stored under `refs/notes/entire`, one ref total. The tree hash points to the agent's file snapshot. Objects referenced by notes are reachable.\\n\\nDownside: notes are per-commit, so split commits need the note on the first commit to reference blobs consumed by the second commit. Awkward lifecycle.\\n\\n## My recommendation: Option 2\\n\\nEmbedding snapshots in `entire/checkpoints/v1` is the cleanest because:\\n\\n- **Zero extra refs** — no shadow branches, no custom refs, no notes\\n- **Always reachable** — the metadata branch is permanent\\n- **Natural lifecycle** — the snapshot is part of the checkpoint, not a separate thing to manage\\n- **Self-contained checkpoints** — a checkpoint has transcript, metadata, AND the agent's intended file state. You can reconstruct exactly what happened without needing external refs\\n- **Carry-forward reads from permanent storage** — `stagedFilesOverlapWithContent` reads blob content from the checkpoint tree instead of a shadow branch\\n- **No cleanup needed** — when carry-forward completes, you can optionally remove the `snapshot/` subtree from the next checkpoint commit, or just leave it (it's useful historical data)\\n\\nThe flow becomes:\\n\\n1. **Active session**: shadow branch works as today (needed for SaveStep before any commit)\\n2. **First commit**: condense to `entire/checkpoints/v1` **including file snapshots** → delete shadow branch immediately\\n3. **Carry-forward**: session state has `source_checkpoint_id` → read snapshot blobs from checkpoint tree on metadata branch\\n4. **Subsequent commits**: compare against snapshot → update carry-forward state → when empty, `FullyCondensed=true`\\n5. **Session ends**: no lingering refs. Shadow branch was already deleted at step 2.\\n\\nThe shadow branch's lifetime shrinks from \\\"session start → all carry-forward complete\\\" to just \\\"session start → first commit\\\". For ENDED sessions doing split commits, there's no shadow branch at all.\\n\\nWant me to dig into the implementation specifics of this approach?\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":495,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":106659,\"output_tokens\":4522,\"server_tool_use\":{\"web_search_requests\":0,\"web_fetch_requests\":0},\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":495,\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0},\"inference_geo\":\"\",\"iterations\":[],\"speed\":\"standard\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYkdSxMR1NRVG83yfMLcs\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"9ea923b1-0c9c-4351-9343-556580b3a289\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:19:27.869Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"9ea923b1-0c9c-4351-9343-556580b3a289\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"Stop\",\"hookName\":\"Stop\",\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-cod