er\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"can you explain option 4 more?\"},\"uuid\":\"fa372274-e3e8-4c8d-8c7a-f19772c0f253\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:26:51.730Z\",\"permissionMode\":\"bypassPermissions\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"fa372274-e3e8-4c8d-8c7a-f19772c0f253\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01PBDxD5GnUzPnE8VTx1ydgh\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"The user wants more detail on the single accumulator ref approach. Let me think through this more carefully.\\n\\nThe idea is: instead of having N shadow branches (one per session/base-commit), have a single ref that holds ALL carry-forward file blobs across all sessions. This ref points to a tree that's organized by session ID.\\n\\nLet me think through the full lifecycle and mechanics.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":4474,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":107154,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":4474},\"output_tokens\":8,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYke9YHxGYrzrHwwKxc83\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"9c5b55ad-f231-4765-85dc-794948c89701\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:26:57.089Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"9c5b55ad-f231-4765-85dc-794948c89701\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01PBDxD5GnUzPnE8VTx1ydgh\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"## Option 4: Single accumulator ref\\n\\nThe idea: instead of N shadow branches (`refs/heads/entire/<hash>-<worktree>`) — one per session — maintain a **single tree** that holds all carry-forward blobs for all active sessions.\\n\\n### Where it lives\\n\\nIt could be a subtree on `entire/checkpoints/v1` itself, or a dedicated ref like `refs/entire/snapshots`. Let's say it's a well-known path on the metadata branch:\\n\\n```\\nentire/checkpoints/v1 tree:\\n├── a3/b2c4d5e6f7/          ← checkpoint data (existing)\\n│   ├── metadata.json\\n│   └── 0/full.jsonl\\n├── ff/0011223344/           ← another checkpoint\\n│   └── ...\\n└── _carry_forward/          ← NEW: single location for all sessions\\n    ├── <session-id-1>/\\n    │   ├── src/auth.go      ← blob: what the agent wrote\\n    │   └── src/main.go\\n    └── <session-id-2>/\\n        └── lib/utils.py\\n```\\n\\nAll blobs under `_carry_forward/` are reachable via the `entire/checkpoints/v1` ref. One ref, any number of sessions.\\n\\n### Lifecycle\\n\\n**Step 1: First commit (condensation)**\\n\\nThe session has files A, B, C. User commits A, B.\\n\\nCondensation writes:\\n- Checkpoint metadata + transcript to `a3/b2c4d5e6f7/` (as today)\\n- Agent's version of file C to `_carry_forward/<session-id>/src/C.go`\\n\\nShadow branch is deleted immediately.\\n\\n**Step 2: Second commit**\\n\\nPostCommit sees the ENDED session has carry-forward. It:\\n1. Reads `_carry_forward/<session-id>/src/C.go` blob hash from the metadata branch tree\\n2. Compares against the committed file's blob hash\\n3. If match (or working tree is clean) → carry-forward complete\\n4. Writes a new commit on `entire/checkpoints/v1` that removes `_carry_forward/<session-id>/` from the tree\\n\\nIf the user commits with `git add -p` (partial), file C still has remaining changes:\\n- Compare hashes → still differ\\n- Check working tree → still dirty\\n- File C stays in `_carry_forward/`\\n\\n**Step 3: Third commit (remaining hunks)**\\n\\nSame check. This time committed hash matches or working tree is clean. Remove from `_carry_forward/`.\\n\\n**Step N: Cleanup**\\n\\nWhen a session's subtree under `_carry_forward/` becomes empty, the session is fully condensed. If ALL sessions are done, `_carry_forward/` disappears from the tree entirely.\\n\\n### What changes vs today\\n\\n| Operation | Today | Accumulator |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| SaveStep (active session) | Write to shadow branch | Same (shadow branch still needed during active session) |\\n| First commit | Condense + carry-forward creates new shadow branch | Condense + write carry-forward blobs to metadata branch |\\n| Subsequent commit | Read shadow branch for comparison | Read `_carry_forward/` from metadata branch |\\n| Content comparison | `shadowTree.File(path)` | `metadataTree.File(\\\"_carry_forward/\\\" + sessionID + \\\"/\\\" + path)` |\\n| Cleanup | Delete shadow branch when done | Remove subtree from next metadata commit |\\n| Stale session | Shadow branch lingers 7 days | `_carry_forward/` entries can have timestamps, clean up aggressively |\\n\\n### The key advantage over per-session refs\\n\\nWith shadow branches (or any per-session ref), you get ref proliferation:\\n- 3 sessions with carry-forward = 3 refs\\n- Each needs individual lifecycle management\\n- `git for-each-ref` output grows\\n- Push/fetch exclusion rules needed for each\\n\\nWith the accumulator:\\n- 3 sessions with carry-forward = 1 ref, 3 subtrees\\n- Adding/removing sessions is just a tree mutation on a branch you already commit to\\n- No new refs ever created for carry-forward\\n- The metadata branch is already pushed/excluded as a unit\\n\\n### Where it gets interesting\\n\\nSince we're already writing commits to `entire/checkpoints/v1` during condensation, adding carry-forward blobs to the same commit is essentially free — it's the same tree-building operation. And reading from it in PostCommit is the same `tree.File()` call we already do for checkpoint metadata.\\n\\nThe shadow branch still exists for the **active session** (between SaveStep calls, before any commit). But its lifetime shrinks to: `first SaveStep → first commit`. After that, everything lives on the metadata branch.\\n\\n### The nuance vs Option 2\\n\\nOption 2 puts the snapshot **inside the checkpoint directory** (`a3/b2c4d5e6f7/snapshot/`). Option 4 puts it in a **shared location** (`_carry_forward/<session-id>/`).\\n\\nThe difference matters for multi-commit carry-forward:\\n- **Option 2**: After commit 2, you'd need to update the snapshot inside an existing checkpoint directory, or create a new checkpoint entry just for the carry-forward update. Mixing \\\"checkpoint data\\\" with \\\"mutable carry-forward state\\\" feels awkward.\\n- **Option 4**: The `_carry_forward/` area is explicitly mutable — entries come and go. Checkpoint directories stay immutable once written. Clean separation of concerns.\\n\\nDoes this make more sense as a direction? The `_carry_forward/` subtree is essentially \\\"the shadow branch, but stored on the metadata branch instead of as a separate ref.\\\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":4474,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":107154,\"output_tokens\":1440,\"server_tool_use\":{\"web_search_requests\":0,\"web_fetch_requests\":0},\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":4474,\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0},\"inference_geo\":\"\",\"iterations\":[],\"speed\":\"standard\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYke9YHxGYrzrHwwKxc83\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"b3de86d7-2c50-41ea-ace0-39f1f6ea7633\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:27:26.286Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"b3de86d7-2c50-41ea-ace0-39f1f6ea7633\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug