69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01KNSZ9HP5CPX2PkEdFA2bnR\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"The user is asking about how the shadow branch works vs just storing blobs. Let me think about this carefully.\\n\\nThe shadow branch currently works like this:\\n- It's based off the HEAD commit (base commit)\\n- When `buildTreeWithChanges` runs, it starts from the HEAD tree (the `baseTreeHash`) and overlays the agent's modified files on top\\n- So the shadow branch tree is: HEAD's full tree + agent's file modifications overlaid\\n\\nThis means the shadow branch tree contains ALL files — both the unchanged ones from HEAD and the modified ones from the agent. The \\\"diff\\\" is implicit: compare the shadow tree against HEAD tree, and the differences are what the agent changed.\\n\\nWhen `filesWithRemainingAgentChanges` runs, it compares:\\n\\n\\n- The committed file hash from the new HEAD after a commit\\n- The shadow file hash to see if the agent's changes were fully applied\\n\\nIf they match, the agent's version was committed; if they differ, there are remaining changes. With the blob storage approach, I'd only keep the agent-modified files and compare their hashes against what got committed to determine what still needs to be carried forward.\\n\\nFor detecting overlaps, the logic varies by scenario: modified files just check existence in the parent tree, new files compare blob hashes, and staged files may need to read the actual blob content to check for significant overlap. The working tree comparison doesn't involve the shadow at all—it's purely about what's committed versus what's on disk.\\n\\nActually, I think I'm overcomplicating this. The shadow branch is built from HEAD, so it already contains all the files the agent touched. When we look up a file in the shadow tree, we get the agent's version of it. If we only stored the modified files, we'd still retrieve the same blob for any file the agent changed. The real question is whether we ever need the base version for comparison—but the current logic doesn't compute diffs between shadow and base, just between shadow and HEAD's committed state.\\n\\nLooking at the actual operations: checking for remaining agent changes, detecting overlaps with new files, and reading file contents—none of these require knowing what the base tree was. They all just need the individual file blobs from the shadow itself. So the answer is no, we don't need to preserve that context.\\n\\nThe shadow branch already stores complete file blobs, not diffs. When you access a file from the shadow tree, you get the full content. The \\\"diff\\\" is computed on-the-fly by comparing blobs, whether they come from a shadow branch or a carry-forward ref—the mechanism works identically either way.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":532,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":113110,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":532},\"output_tokens\":8,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYkegj7SZGZD3rPVGDeAK\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"07ef9bb9-b1d1-449c-b0d2-ee91beab6a1c\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:34:23.545Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"07ef9bb9-b1d1-449c-b0d2-ee91beab6a1c\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01KNSZ9HP5CPX2PkEdFA2bnR\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"You're right to question this, but I think the blobs actually work the same way. Let me clarify what the shadow branch stores today.\\n\\nWhen `buildTreeWithChanges` runs, it takes the **HEAD tree** (all files) and overlays the agent's modified files on top. So the shadow branch tree is:\\n\\n```\\nshadow tree = HEAD tree + agent's modifications overlaid\\n```\\n\\nIt's a complete tree — every file in the repo. When you do `shadowTree.File(\\\"src/auth.go\\\")`, you get back the **whole file blob** (the agent's version), not a diff/patch.\\n\\nThe \\\"diff\\\" is never stored. It's always computed dynamically by comparing two blobs:\\n\\n```go\\n// filesWithRemainingAgentChanges:\\nif commitFile.Hash == shadowFile.Hash {  // compare two whole-file blobs\\n    // fully committed\\n}\\n```\\n\\nSo when we read `shadowFile` from the shadow branch, we're getting the complete file content — the same thing we'd store in the carry-forward ref. The base tree context in the shadow branch is only there because `buildTreeWithChanges` needs *some* starting tree to overlay onto. The unchanged files in that tree are never read by any carry-forward logic.\\n\\nTo verify — every place that reads from the shadow tree for carry-forward purposes:\\n\\n| Function | What it reads | Needs base tree? |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| `filesWithRemainingAgentChanges` | `shadowFile.Hash` | No — hash comparison only |\\n| `filesOverlapWithContent` | `shadowFile.Hash` | No — checks `parentTree` separately for modified files |\\n| `stagedFilesOverlapWithContent` | `shadowFile.Hash` + `shadowFile.Contents()` | No — reads the blob directly |\\n| `workingTreeMatchesCommit` | Doesn't use shadow at all | N/A |\\n\\nNone of them need \\\"shadow file minus base file.\\\" They all just need the agent's file blob.\\n\\nSo the carry-forward ref storing only the modified files' blobs is functionally identical to reading those same blobs from the full shadow tree — we just skip storing the thousands of unchanged files from HEAD that nobody reads.\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache