\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"type\":\"system\",\"subtype\":\"turn_duration\",\"durationMs\":37213,\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:34:33.039Z\",\"uuid\":\"2f887a1d-7ec5-4c0e-a5bb-7b2a48f5b3c0\",\"isMeta\":false}\n{\"type\":\"file-history-snapshot\",\"messageId\":\"db041abd-85b9-44b3-8696-2be6700787a5\",\"snapshot\":{\"messageId\":\"db041abd-85b9-44b3-8696-2be6700787a5\",\"trackedFileBackups\":{},\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:36:32.682Z\"},\"isSnapshotUpdate\":false}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"2f887a1d-7ec5-4c0e-a5bb-7b2a48f5b3c0\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"but how is the filesOverlapWithContent then done? Like how can it differentiate with which lines were already there and which are actually changed?\"},\"uuid\":\"db041abd-85b9-44b3-8696-2be6700787a5\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:36:31.487Z\",\"permissionMode\":\"bypassPermissions\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"db041abd-85b9-44b3-8696-2be6700787a5\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01XBA36PXhH16HB4KJF5vbeo\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"The user is asking a really good question. Let me re-read `filesOverlapWithContent` carefully.\\n\\n```go\\nfor _, filePath := range filesTouched {\\n    headFile, err := headTree.File(filePath)\\n    if err != nil {\\n        // File not in HEAD commit. Check if this is a deletion\\n        if parentTree != nil {\\n            if _, parentErr := parentTree.File(filePath); parentErr == nil {\\n                return true // deletion counts as overlap\\n            }\\n        }\\n        continue\\n    }\\n\\n    // Check if this is a modified file (exists in parent) or new file\\n    isModified := false\\n\\n\\n```\\n\\nI'm checking whether each file was modified or newly created, then handling them differently. Modified files always trigger an overlap, while new files only count as overlapping if their content matches what's in the shadow branch.\\n\\nThe key insight is that `filesOverlapWithContent` doesn't actually look at *which lines* changed—it just checks whether a file was touched by both the agent and the commit. The more granular comparison happens in `stagedFilesOverlapWithContent`, which does line-by-line analysis for new files.\\n\\nBut even that's not doing a true diff against a base state. It's comparing staged content against shadow content without understanding what was already there before the agent started. And `filesWithRemainingAgentChanges` just compares whole-file blob hashes.\\n\\nSo the honest answer is: the current system doesn't actually implement line-level attribution. It operates at the file level with blob comparisons, and the shadow branch's base tree isn't really being leveraged for anything that the file hashes alone wouldn't tell us.\\n\\nThe user is pointing out that storing just blobs would lose the ability to compute a diff against the base — and they're right. But we're not using that ability anyway. All the carry-forward logic is blob-level, never computing tree diffs.\\n\\nThey might also be hinting at a deeper gap: the current implementation is file-level, not hunk-level. If you partially commit a file with `git add -p`, the carry-forward detects the file still has changes, but it doesn't track which specific hunks were committed. This could be what they mean about the shadow branch not working like true staging — and maybe any new approach should address that.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":1606,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":113642,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":1606},\"output_tokens\":8,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYketGtCYAnrqkU4vyTnV\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"c47531eb-ce2e-46b3-bef0-ff2057c10441\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:36:58.662Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"c47531eb-ce2e-46b3-bef0-ff2057c10441\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01XBA36PXhH16HB4KJF5vbeo\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"That's the thing — it doesn't. Look at what `filesOverlapWithContent` actually does for each case:\\n\\n**Modified files** (existed in parent, exists in HEAD):\\n```go\\nisModified := false\\nif parentTree != nil {\\n    if _, err := parentTree.File(filePath); err == nil {\\n        isModified = true\\n    }\\n}\\n\\n// Modified files always count as overlap\\nif isModified {\\n    return true\\n}\\n```\\n\\nIt just checks: \\\"did this filename exist before AND was it changed in this commit AND is it in the session's `filesTouched`?\\\" If yes → overlap. It doesn't look at which lines changed at all. It doesn't read the shadow content. It doesn't diff anything.\\n\\n**New files** (didn't exist in parent):\\n```go\\nif headFile.Hash == shadowFile.Hash {\\n    return true  // exact blob match\\n}\\n```\\n\\nWhole-file hash comparison. No line awareness.\\n\\n**`filesWithRemainingAgentChanges`** — same story:\\n```go\\nif commitFile.Hash == shadowFile.Hash {\\n    // fully committed, done\\n}\\n// else: check if working tree is clean\\n```\\n\\nWhole-file blob comparison. If the hash matches, file is done. If not, check if the working tree still has changes.\\n\\n**So the shadow branch's base tree is effectively unused for carry-forward.** The base tree is there because `buildTreeWithChanges` builds on top of HEAD as a convenience, but no carry-forward code ever computes `diff(base, shadow)` to figure out which lines the agent changed.\\n\\nThe line-level awareness you're describing — \\\"the agent changed lines 20-24 and 100-120, user committed lines 20-24, so lines 100-120 remain\\\" — **doesn't exist today**. The current system works at file granularity:\\n\\n1. Agent touched `auth.go`\\n2. User commits `auth.go` with `git add -p` (partial hunks)\\n3. `commitFile.Hash != shadowFile.Hash` → hashes differ\\n4. `workingTreeMatchesCommit()` → working tree still dirty\\n5. → keep `auth.go` in carry-forward\\n\\nIt correctly detects \\\"there's still something uncommitted\\\" but doesn't know *what*. It just keeps the whole file in carry-forward and checks again on the next commit.\\n\\nSo to answer your question directly: moving from shadow branches to a carry-forward ref with just the agent's file blobs loses nothing — because the base-tree diff capability was never used. The carry-forward ref approach would be functionally identical to what exists today.\\n\\nBut this also means: if you *want* hunk-level tracking in the future (knowing exactly which lines remain uncommitted), neither approach gives you that. That would require actually computing and storing diffs, which is a different feature entirely. Is that something you want to explore, or is the current file-level granularity sufficient?\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":1606,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":113642,\"output_