/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"type\":\"system\",\"subtype\":\"turn_duration\",\"durationMs\":39875,\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:37:12.558Z\",\"uuid\":\"ef7c6ce4-af4d-477f-804b-a6d00ee2000e\",\"isMeta\":false}\n{\"type\":\"file-history-snapshot\",\"messageId\":\"9f083083-8c62-46a1-9381-7e5b14afef4e\",\"snapshot\":{\"messageId\":\"9f083083-8c62-46a1-9381-7e5b14afef4e\",\"trackedFileBackups\":{},\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:38:56.800Z\"},\"isSnapshotUpdate\":false}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"ef7c6ce4-af4d-477f-804b-a6d00ee2000e\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"I mean a shadow branch based on current head containing one commit, that has the diff implicitly right? It just doesn't work anymore with carry forward\"},\"uuid\":\"9f083083-8c62-46a1-9381-7e5b14afef4e\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:38:55.517Z\",\"permissionMode\":\"bypassPermissions\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"9f083083-8c62-46a1-9381-7e5b14afef4e\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01Xxxt1dDhdQbdENwrdz5N7j\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"The user is making an important point. Let me think about this carefully.\\n\\nThe shadow branch is based on HEAD. So:\\n\\n- HEAD tree = the state of files before the agent started\\n- Shadow tree = HEAD tree + agent's modifications\\n\\nIf you diff these two trees, you get exactly what the agent changed. The diff is implicit in the relationship between the two trees. You don't need to store it explicitly — git can compute `diff(HEAD, shadow)` at any time.\\n\\nThis works perfectly for the FIRST commit. You have:\\n- Parent of the commit (≈ HEAD when session started, ≈ base of shadow branch)\\n- Shadow tree (agent's intended state)\\n\\n\\n- Committed tree\\n\\nYou can compute what the agent changed, what was actually committed, and what remains uncommitted. But here's where it breaks down: after the first commit, HEAD moves forward and the shadow branch gets rebased onto the new HEAD. Now the shadow tree represents new HEAD plus the remaining working tree changes. The issue is that when carrying forward, the working tree contains all the files, not just the uncommitted changes, so the logic for determining what's actually new gets muddled.\\n\\nLet me trace through a concrete example: the agent modifies auth.go in two separate sections, the shadow branch captures both changes, and we can see exactly what changed. Then the user commits just one section, HEAD advances, and we create a new shadow branch based on the updated HEAD. The working tree still has the second section modified, so the carry-forward should preserve that—but now the base has shifted to include the first commit's changes, which complicates how we calculate what's actually new versus what was already committed. So the working tree still contains the full agent version with both the committed lines and the new changes, while the new HEAD only has the committed portion. When `WriteTemporary` builds the shadow tree from the new HEAD plus the remaining working tree files, the diff between them correctly shows only the uncommitted changes. This carry-forward mechanism preserves the implicit diff even after the commit moves forward.\\n\\nBut there's still something to consider—\\n\\nonce the shadow branch is deleted and we're relying on a carry-forward ref that just stores the full agent blob, we lose that base reference entirely. We'd only have the agent's complete version and the committed version to compare against, with no intermediate reference point. The carry-forward blob represents the full agent state including both the committed lines and the new changes, so after the first commit lands those initial lines, the agent still has that complete blob but the HEAD has moved forward. The question becomes whether the carry-forward mechanism can still correctly identify what's actually new versus what's already been committed.\\n\\nThe tricky part is when the user makes their own edits between commits. If the user adds lines beyond what the agent wrote, the committed blob won't match the agent's blob anymore, but the existing `workingTreeMatchesCommit` check should catch that and recognize the user intentionally made those changes. So the carry-forward ref approach might actually work just as well, though I need to trace through an edge case where the agent writes multiple separate changes and the user commits them piecemeal while also adding their own modifications.\\n\\nThe user's deeper point is that the shadow branch approach has an implicit advantage: the shadow is anchored to a specific commit, so you naturally get a diff. With just stored blobs, you have the agent's intended state but lose that base reference. That's a real conceptual difference, even if the current implementation doesn't actually rely on computing the diff directly.\\n\\nThe user seems to be arguing we should build the system properly now to support hunk-level tracking later, rather than painting ourselves into a corner. But then they also note that the shadow branch's implicit diff breaks down during carry-forward anyway, since the base itself changes. Let me think through whether that's actually true—after carry-forward, the new shadow base would be the updated commit, and diffing against that would still give us the right hunks.\\n\\nActually, the diff still works correctly after carry-forward because the shadow branch gets recreated with the new HEAD as its base. The real problem only emerges if you delete the shadow branch entirely and try to rely on just blob hashes—then you've lost the base and can't reconstruct the diff at all. But the current implementation doesn't even attempt to compute diffs; it only compares blobs directly.\\n\\nLet me reconsider what the user means. They're pointing out that while a shadow branch does implicitly contain the diff (the difference between shadow tree and base), this approach breaks down with carry-forward because the shadow branch needs to persist for potentially days after a session ends, creating a lifecycle management problem. The blob-only approach solves that by eliminating the lingering refs, but at the cost of losing that implicit diff capability. I'm wondering if the carry-forward mechanism is actually preserving the diff correctly—it passes `IsFirstCheckpoint: false` when creating the new shadow branch, which should handle the base transition properly.\\n\\nLooking at the code flow, `WriteTemporary` collects the modified and new files from the working tree, then `buildTreeWithChanges` overlays those file blobs onto the new HEAD's tree. So the shadow tree becomes new HEAD plus the remaining agent changes, and the diff between them captures exactly what the agent modified. That seems right, but there's a subtle edge case: if the user themselves edits a file that the agent also modified between commits, the working tree contains both the agent's changes and the user's new edits, and the carry-forward shadow would include both. The diff would then only show the agent's original lines, not the user's subsequent modifications.\\n\\nActually, this contamination issue already exists in the current carry-forward logic since it reads from the working tree anyway. I think what the user is really getting at is simpler—a shadow branch based on HEAD with one commit on top naturally encodes the agent's changes as a diff, which is elegant. But carry-forward breaks that property because the shadow needs to be rebuilt or persisted in some way, and I'm not quite seeing where they're going with that objection.\\n\\nLet me think about what they're actually asking: can we preserve that nice implicit-diff property while still solving the lifecycle problem of carry-forward, or do we have to accept losing it?\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":1783,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":115248,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":1783},\"output_tokens\":8,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYkf4u9Yom77b4gUv5n6o\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"542d6992-fcc4-442a-bcd3-db10441eaeb0\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:39:54.737Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"542d6992-fcc4-442a-bcd3-db10441eaeb0\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01Xxxt1dDhdQbdENwrdz5N7j\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Yes, exactly. The shadow branch has a really nice property:\\n\\n```\\nbase (HEAD) ← shadow commit\\n     └── the diff between these two IS the agent's changes\\n```\\n\\nGit can compute `diff(base, shadow)` at any time. You don't store the diff — it's implicit in the parent-child relationship. And for the first commit this works perfectly:\\n\\n- `diff(base, shadow)` = everything the agent changed\\n- `diff(parent, committed)` = what the user committed\\n- The remainder = what's left for carry-forward\\n\\nBut the moment you carry forward, this breaks:\\n\\n1. Commit 1 happens → HEAD moves to commit B\\n2. `carryForwardToNewShadowBranch` creates a new shadow based on commit B\\n3. It reads remaining files from the **working tree** and overlays them on B's tree\\n4. The new shadow captures the working tree state, not \\\"the agent's original diff\\\"\\n\\nThe new shadow still \\\"works\\\" for blob comparison (hash equality), but the clean semantic of \\\"one commit = the agent's delta\\\" is lost. The working tree at that point could contain user edits mixed in with remaining agent changes. And if the user reverts some agent changes before commit 2, the carry-forward shadow captures that revert as if it was the agent's intent.\\n\\nSo the fundamental issue is: **the shadow branch gives you a clean diff for exactly one commit. After that, you're working with snapshots, not diffs.**\\n\\nWhich means the carry-forward ref approach (Option 4) doesn't actually lose anything that wasn't already lost. After the first commit, both approaches are equivalent — just blob snapshots being compared by hash.\\n\\nThe real question is: do we want to *fix* this and actually track at the diff/hunk level? Or accept that file-level granularity is good enough for carry-forward? If file-level is fine, then the carry-forward ref is strictly better (cleaner lifecycle, no lingering branches). If you want hunk-level, neither approach works today and we'd need something fundamentally different — like actually storing the patch and tracking which hunks have been consumed.\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":1783,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":115248,\"output_tokens\":3120,\"server_tool_use\":{\"web_search_requests\":0,\"web_fetch_requests\":0},\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":1783,\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0},\"inference_geo\":\"\",\"iterations\":[],\"speed\":\"standard\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYkf4u9Yom77b4gUv5n6o\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"181465be-f449-48