he first commit may change line counts in the same file\\n- The user may add/remove lines in other parts of the file\\n- Rebase can rewrite the entire file\\n\\nOptions:\\n- **Re-diff on each commit**: Recompute `diff(new_base, agent_version)` fresh each time.\\n  Requires keeping the agent's intended file content (blob) reachable.\\n- **Fuzzy hunk matching**: Match hunks by content rather than line numbers (similar to\\n  `git apply --3way`).\\n- **Anchor-based tracking**: Identify hunks by surrounding context lines rather than\\n  absolute positions.\\n\\n### Q5: How does this interact with the shadow branch during active sessions?\\n\\nThe shadow branch is still needed during active sessions (before any commit) for\\n`SaveStep`. The hunk-level tracking only kicks in at carry-forward time (after the\\nfirst commit). So the flow would be:\\n\\n1. **Active session**: Shadow branch as today (stores full file snapshots + transcript)\\n2. **First commit**: Condense to `entire/checkpoints/v1`. Compute and store agent diff.\\n   Delete shadow branch.\\n3. **Carry-forward**: Use stored diff + custom ref for hunk tracking. No shadow branch.\\n4. **Subsequent commits**: Detect consumed hunks, update carry-forward state.\\n5. **All hunks consumed**: Clean up carry-forward state. Session fully condensed.\\n\\n## Research Tasks\\n\\nThe following questions need implementation research:\\n\\n### Research A: Diff computation and storage in Go\\n\\n- What Go libraries exist for computing unified diffs / working with hunks?\\n- Can go-git compute tree-level or file-level diffs efficiently?\\n- What's the performance of diff computation in the context of a git hook?\\n- How to represent a diff compactly in JSON (for session state) vs as a git object?\\n\\n### Research B: Hunk consumption detection\\n\\n- Given an agent diff (base → agent) and a commit diff (parent → commit), what\\n  algorithms exist to determine which agent hunks were \\\"consumed\\\" by the commit?\\n- How does `