ors\":[],\"preventedContinuation\":false,\"stopReason\":\"\",\"hasOutput\":false,\"level\":\"suggestion\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:45:02.410Z\",\"uuid\":\"393dc4de-58d2-4eaf-9d37-bd2715320b26\",\"toolUseID\":\"13f4f48a-aacb-46a3-b374-4565f38237f9\"}\n{\"type\":\"queue-operation\",\"operation\":\"enqueue\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:48:52.774Z\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"content\":\"<task-notification>\\n<task-id>a3a852a2c8fa36ec5</task-id>\\n<tool-use-id>REDACTED</tool-use-id>\\n<status>completed</status>\\n<summary>Agent \\\"Research git-absorb and hunk tracking\\\" completed</summary>\\n<result>Now I have comprehensive research across all the areas. Let me compile the findings.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Research Summary: Hunk Tracking/Matching Algorithms in the Git Ecosystem\\n\\n### 1. git-absorb\\n\\n**How it works:** git-absorb uses **patch commutation** (ported from Facebook's `hg absorb`) to determine which commit a staged hunk belongs to. It walks backward through a range of commits (default: last 10, configurable via `--base`), testing whether each staged hunk \\\"commutes\\\" with each commit.\\n\\n**Commutation algorithm (from `src/commute.rs`):**\\n\\nTwo hunks commute (can be reordered without changing the result) if:\\n1. **Non-overlapping:** The first hunk's lower bound is at or before the second hunk's upper bound. In this case, the \\\"below\\\" hunk's start positions are adjusted by `(added_count - removed_count)` of the \\\"above\\\" hunk.\\n2. **Overlapping but uniform:** Both hunks are exclusively adding (or exclusively removing) the same repeated line. These can be reordered regardless of position.\\n3. **Otherwise:** They do NOT commute, meaning the hunk \\\"belongs to\\\" that commit.\\n\\nWhen a hunk fails to commute with a commit, that commit is identified as the correct target for a fixup. If it commutes with all commits in the range, it remains staged with a warning.\\n\\n**Go port:** No Go port exists. The algorithm is straightforward enough to reimplement. The key data structures are `Hunk` (with `added` and `removed` blocks, each having `start` position and `lines`) and the `commute()` function itself.\\n\\n**Alternative approach -- git-autofixup:** Uses `git blame` instead of commutation. It blames each context line surrounding a hunk and assigns the hunk to a commit if all context lines blame the same topic-branch commit. Has strictness levels (0-2) for increasingly conservative matching.\\n\\n**Relevance to your problem:** The commutation concept is directly applicable. If you have the agent's hunks and want to know if they were \\\"consumed\\\" by a commit, you can test whether each agent hunk commutes with the commit's diff. Non-commuting means the commit touched the same region.\\n\\n**Source:** [tummychow/git-absorb](https://github.com/tummychow/git-absorb), specifically `src/commute.rs`\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2. git range-diff\\n\\n**How it works:** git range-diff matches corresponding commits between two versions of a patch series using a **bipartite graph assignment** algorithm.\\n\\n**Matching algorithm:**\\n1. Compute the diff (patch) for each commit in both ranges\\n2. For every pair of commits (one from each range), compute a \\\"diff of diffs\\\" -- the textual diff between the two patches\\n3. Use the size of each diff-of-diffs as the cost in a cost matrix\\n4. Add dummy nodes for wholly new/removed commits with a fudge-factor cost\\n5. Solve the **minimum-cost assignment** using the **Jonker-Volgenant algorithm** (cubic runtime)\\n\\n**Key insight:** It operates at commit granularity, not hunk granularity. It measures similarity between entire patches, not individual hunks.\\n\\n**Relevance to your problem:** The approach of \\\"diff two diffs and measure similarity\\\" is conceptually useful but heavyweight for your use case. The Jonker-Volgenant assignment is overkill when you have just two diffs to compare (agent diff vs commit diff) rather than two series of commits.\\n\\n**Source:** [git range-diff documentation](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-range-diff), [range-diff.c in git source](https://github.com/git/git/blob/master/range-diff.c)\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 3. Three-Way Merge / diff3\\n\\n**How diff3 works:**\\n1. Compute `diff(O, A)` and `diff(O, B)` where O is the common ancestor\\n2. Align matching regions across all three texts\\n3. Classify each chunk:\\n   - **Both unchanged:** Output the original\\n   - **Only A changed:** Output A's version (A's change)\\n   - **Only B changed:** Output B's version (B's change)\\n   - **Both changed differently:** Conflict\\n\\n**Change attribution:** diff3 inherently tells you which side a change came from. This is exactly the property you need: given base (pre-agent state), A (agent's version), and B (committed version), diff3 classification tells you which agent changes are present in B.\\n\\n**Go implementations:**\\n- [epiclabs-io/diff3](https://github.com/epiclabs-io/diff3) -- Go port of a JS implementation based on Synchrotron. Provides `Merge(a, o, b, detailed, labelA, labelB)` returning a `MergeResult`.\\n- [charlesvdv/go-three-way-merge](https://github.com/charlesvdv/go-three-way-merge) -- Another Go library for three-way merge.\\n- [golang/go#68765](https://github.com/golang/go/issues/68765) -- Ongoing discussion about adding diff3 to Go's standard tools.\\n\\n**Academic reference:** [\\\"A Formal Investigation of Diff3\\\"](https://www.cis.upenn.edu/~bcpierce/papers/diff3-short.pdf) by Khanna, Kuber, and Pierce (FSTTCS 2007) -- formal analysis of diff3 properties and guarantees about non-conflicting edits to well-separated regions.\\n\\n**Relevance to your problem:** This is highly applicable. With three versions (base, agent-version, committed-version), diff3 can classify every chunk as \\\"agent-only change,\\\" \\\"commit-only change,\\\" \\\"both changed identically\\\" (consumed), or \\\"conflict\\\" (modified differently). This directly answers \\\"which agent hunks were included in the commit.\\\"\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 4. Patch Algebra / Hunk Intersection\\n\\n**Darcs patch commutation:**\\nTwo hunk patches on the same file commute if their line ranges do not overlap. When they do commute, you adjust line offsets. When they overlap, you have a conflict (cannot commute). The formal rule from Darcs (Haskell):\\n- If `p1` occurs in an earlier part of the file than `p2`, they commute by adjusting line offsets\\n- If they overlap in line ranges, they do NOT commute -- this signals a dependency/conflict\\n\\n**Pijul's category-theoretic approach:**\\nMerge is defined as a **pushout** in a category where files are objects and patches are arrows. The key paper is [\\\"A Categorical Theory of Patches\\\"](https://arxiv.org/abs/1311.3903) by Mimram and Di Giusto. The core insight: the \\\"free completion under finite colimits\\\" of the file category gives you a system where every pair of patches has a well-defined merge (pushout), with conflicts represented as objects labeled by lines with ordering relations.\\n\\n**Homotopical Patch Theory** (Angiuli, Morehouse, Licata, Harper -- [CMU paper](https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~rwh/papers/htpt/jfp.pdf)): Models patch theory using higher inductive types in homotopy type theory, separating the formal theory from the repository interpretation.\\n\\n**Relevance to your problem:** Patch commutation from Darcs is the most directly applicable concept. The question \\\"did this commit consume this agent hunk?\\\" is equivalent to \\\"does this agent hunk commute with the commit's inverse?\\\" If not, the regions overlap and the hunk was (at least partially) consumed. The category-theoretic approaches are elegant but impractical to implement for your use case.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 5. Code Review Tools\\n\\n**Gerrit -- `GitPositionTransformer` and `CommentPorter`:**\\n\\nGerrit's ported-comments feature (introduced in 3.4) maps comment positions across patchsets using a two-phase algorithm:\\n\\n1. **File path resolution:** Handle renamed/deleted/copied files\\n2. **Line range shifting:** Process range mappings sequentially top-to-bottom, tracking cumulative line shifts. If a comment's position falls within a changed range, it uses a conflict strategy (either omit the position or degrade to file-level).\\n\\nKey classes: `GitPositionTransformer` (handles the position mapping), `CommentPorter` (orchestrates porting of unresolved comments across patchsets). The algorithm is essentially: walk through the diff hunks, maintaining a running offset, and adjust comment line numbers accordingly. Comments on changed lines get marked as conflicting/outdated.\\n\\n**GitHub:**\\nGitHub tracks which lines were modified between force-pushes. Comments on lines that changed in a subsequent push are marked \\\"outdated.\\\" The algorithm is simpler than Gerrit's -- if the line a comment was on is part of a changed hunk in the new push, it's outdated.\\n\\n**Gitea:**\\nUses `git blame` to track whether commented lines changed, automatically marking outdated comments. Has known issues with incorrect line number tracking after insertions.\\n\\n**Relevance to your problem:** Gerrit's `GitPositionTransformer` pattern (sequential range-mapping with cumulative offset tracking) is a practical, proven approach for mapping line positions across diffs. This is useful if you need to track \\\"where did this agent hunk end up after the commit.\\\"\\n\\n**Source:** [Gerrit source at googlesource.com](https://gerrit.googlesource.com/gerrit/)\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 6. Practical Approaches\\n\\nGiven the agent's diff (`base -> agent_version`) and a commit's diff (`parent -> commit`), here are the approaches ranked by simplicity and reliability:\\n\\n**Approach A: Three-way diff (RECOMMENDED)**\\n\\nThis is the simplest reliable algorithm:\\n\\n1. You have three versions of each file: `base` (before agent), `agent_version` (agent's changes), `committed_version` (what was actually committed)\\n2. Run diff3 with `base` as the ancestor, `agent_version` as side A, `committed_version` as side B\\n3. Classification:\\n   - Chunks where A changed but B matches base = **agent changes NOT committed** (remaining)\\n   - Chunks where B changed but A matches base = **user's own changes** (not from agent)\\n   - Chunks where both A and B changed identically = **agent changes COMMITTED** (consumed)\\n   - Chunks where both changed differently = **agent changes MODIFIED** by user (partially consumed)\\n\\nThis leverages diff3's inherent change-attribution. Go libraries: [epiclabs-io/diff3](https://github.com/epiclabs-io/diff3) or [charlesvdv/go-three-way-merge](https://github.com/charlesvdv/go-three-way-merge).\\n\\n**Approach B: Residual diff**\\n\\n1. Compute `diff(agent_version, committed_version)` -- this is the \\\"residual\\\"\\n2. If the residual is empty for a file, all agent changes were committed verbatim\\n3. If the residual contains hunks, analyze them against the original agent diff to determine which hunks remain\\n4. Limitation: Cannot distinguish \\\"user removed an agent change\\\" from \\\"user added their own change\\\" without the base version\\n\\n**Approach C: Reverse-apply check**\\n\\n1. For each hunk in the agent's diff, try `git apply --reverse --check` against the committed version\\n2. If reverse-apply succeeds for a hunk, that hunk was consumed (its changes are present)\\n3. If it fails, the hunk was not consumed or was modified\\n4. Limitation: Context-sensitive -- may fail due to surrounding changes even when the core change is present. Also requires shelling out to git per hunk, which is expensive.\\n\\n**Approach D: Hunk-level line-range overlap (simplest approximation)**\\n\\n1. Parse both diffs into hunks per file using [sourcegraph/go-diff](https://github.com/sourcegraph/go-diff) or [bluekeyes/go-gitdiff](https://github.com/bluekeyes/go-gitdiff)\\n2. For each agent hunk, check if the commit's diff has a hunk touching the same line range in the same file\\n3. If the commit hunk's added lines contain the agent hunk's added lines (substring/subsequence match), the agent hunk was consumed\\n4. Limitation: Fragile with split/reorganized hunks and line-offset shifts\\n\\n**Approach E: Commutation test (git-absorb style)**\\n\\n1. Parse the agent's diff and the commit's diff into hunks\\n2. For each agent hunk, test if it commutes with each commit hunk (using the algorithm from git-absorb's `commute.rs`)\\n3. Non-commuting means the commit touched the same region -- the agent hunk was likely consumed\\n4. To confirm consumption vs. conflict, compare the actual line content\\n5. Advantage: Well-founded in patch theory. Disadvantage: Requires implementing the commutation logic.\\n\\n**Recommendation:** Approach A (three-way diff) is the most reliable and semantically clean. You already have all three versions available (the checkpoint stores the base state, the agent produced its version, and the commit is the committed version). The diff3 algorithm gives you exactly the classification you need, with proven Go libraries available. It handles edge cases like line reordering and partial hunk inclusion naturally.\\n\\nFor a quick-and-dirty first pass, Approach D (hunk overlap) combined with content matching gives a good approximation and is easy to implement with existing Go diff libraries.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Key Go Libraries for Implementation\\n\\n| Library | Purpose | Link |\\n|---------|---------|------|\\n| `sourcegraph/go-diff` | Unified diff parsing, `FileDiff`/`Hunk` structs | [pkg.go.dev](https://pkg.go.dev/sourcegraph.com/sourcegraph/go-diff/diff) |\\n| `bluekeyes/go-gitdiff` | Git diff parsing + patch application | [github.com](https://github.com/bluekeyes/go-gitdiff) |\\n| `epiclabs-io/diff3` | Three-way merge with conflict detection | [github.com](https://github.com/epiclabs-io/diff3) |\\n| `charlesvdv/go-three-way-merge` | Three-way merge on text | [github.com](https://github.com/charlesvdv/go-three-way-merge) |\\n| `go-git/go-git` | Git operations (already in your codebase) | [github.com](https://github.com/go-git/go-git) |\\n\\n### Key Academic Papers\\n\\n| Paper | Authors | Relevance |\\n|-------|---------|-----------|\\n| [A Formal Investigation of Diff3](https://www.cis.upenn.edu/~bcpierce/papers/diff3-short.pdf) | Khanna, Kuber, Pierce (2007) | Formal properties of diff3, guarantees about well-separated edits |\\n| [A Categorical Theory of Patches](https://arxiv.org/abs/1311.3903) | Mimram, Di Giusto (2013) | Merge as pushout, theoretical foundation for patch intersection |\\n| [Homotopical Patch Theory](https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~rwh/papers/htpt/jfp.pdf) | Angiuli, Morehouse, Licata, Harper (2014/2016) | Patch theory via higher inductive types |\\n| [Darcs Patch Theory](https://www.cs.tufts.edu/~nr/cs257/archive/david-roundy/Theory%20of%20patches.html) | Roundy | Original theory of patch commutation |\\n| [Ganesh Patch Algebra](https://darcs.net/Theory/GaneshPatchAlgebra) | Sittampalam et al. | Formal properties of patch commutation |\\n\\nSources:\\n- [tummychow/git-absorb](https://github.com/tummychow/git-absorb)\\n- [Super-charging git rebase with git absorb](https://andrewlock.net/super-charging-git-rebase-with-git-absorb/)\\n- [torbiak/git-autofixup](https://github.com/torbiak/git-autofixup)\\n- [Absorb changes across a topic branch](https://torbiak.com/post/autofixup/)\\n- [git range-diff documentation](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-range-diff)\\n- [git/range-diff.c source](https://github.com/git/git/blob/master/range-diff.c)\\n- [diff3 Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diff3)\\n- [Merging with diff3 - The If Works](https://blog.jcoglan.com/2017/05/08/merging-with-diff3/)\\n- [epiclabs-io/diff3 (Go)](https://github.com/epiclabs-io/diff3)\\n- [charlesvdv/go-three-way-merge (Go)](https://github.com/charlesvdv/go-three-way-merge)\\n- [golang/go#68765 - three-way merge](https://github.com/golang/go/issues/68765)\\n- [Understanding Darcs/Patch theory](https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Understanding_Darcs/Patch_theory)\\n- [Darcs Patch Algebra](https://darcs.net/Theory/GaneshPatchAlgebra)\\n- [Pijul Model](https://pijul.org/model/)\\n- [Part 1: Merging and patches](https://jneem.github.io/merging/)\\n- [Gerrit 3.4.x release notes](https://www.gerritcodereview.com/3.4.html)\\n- [Gerrit Review UI](https://gerrit-review.googlesource.com/Documentation/user-review-ui.html)\\n- [GitHub PR commenting docs](https://docs.github.com/en/pull-requests/collaborating-with-pull-requests/reviewing-changes-in-pull-requests/commenting-on-a-pull-request)\\n- [sourcegraph/go-diff](https://github.com/sourcegraph/go-diff)\\n- [bluekeyes/go-gitdiff](https://github.com/bluekeyes/go-gitdiff)\\n- [git-apply documentation](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-apply)\\n- [A Formal Investigation of Diff3](https://www.cis.upenn.edu/~bcpierce/papers/diff3-short.pdf)\\n- [A Categorical Theory of Patches](https://arxiv.org/abs/1311.3903)\\n- [Homotopical Patch Theory](https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~rwh/papers/htpt/jfp.pdf)</result>\\n<usage><total_tokens>49177</total_tokens><tool_uses>49</tool_uses><duration_ms>336310</duration_ms></usage>\\n</task-notification>\\nFull transcript available at: /tmp/claude-1000/-Users-soph-Work-entire-devenv-cli/tasks/a3a852a2c8fa36ec5.output\"}\n{\"type\":\"queue-operation\",\"operation\":\"dequeue\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:48:52.794Z\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"393dc4de-58d2-4eaf-9d37-bd2715320b26\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"<task-notification>\\n<task-id>a3a852a2c8fa36ec5</task-id>\\n<tool-use-id>REDACTED</tool-use-id>\\n<status>completed</status>\\n<summary>Agent \\\"Research git-absorb and hunk tracking\\\" completed</summary>\\n<result>Now I have comprehensive research across all the areas. Let me compile the findings.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Research Summary: Hunk Tracking/Matching Algorithms in the Git Ecosystem\\n\\n### 1. git-absorb\\n\\n**How it works:** git-absorb uses **patch commutation** (ported from Facebook's `hg absorb`) to determine which commit a staged hunk belongs to. It walks backward through a range of commits (default: last 10, configurable via `--base`), testing whether each staged hunk \\\"commutes\\\" with each commit.\\n\\n**Commutation algorithm (from `src/commute.rs`):**\\n\\nTwo hunks commute (can be reordered without changing the result) if:\\n1. **Non-overlapping:** The first hunk's lower bound is at or before the second hunk's upper bound. In this case, the \\\"below\\\" hunk's start positions are adjusted by `(added_count - removed_count)` of the \\\"above\\\" hunk.\\n2. **Overlapping but uniform:** Both hunks are exclusively adding (or exclusively removing) the same repeated line. These can be reordered regardless of position.\\n3. **Otherwise:** They do NOT commute, meaning the hunk \\\"belongs to\\\" that commit.\\n\\nWhen a hunk fails to commute with a commit, that commit is identified as the correct target for a fixup. If it commutes with all commits in the range, it remains staged with a warning.\\n\\n**Go port:** No Go port exists. The algorithm is straightforward enough to reimplement. The key data structures are `Hunk` (with `added` and `removed` blocks, each having `start` position and `lines`) and the `commute()` function itself.\\n\\n**Alternative approach -- git-autofixup:** Uses `git blame` instead of commutation. It blames each context line surrounding a hunk and assigns the hunk to a commit if all context lines blame the same topic-branch commit. Has strictness levels (0-2) for increasingly conservative matching.\\n\\n**Relevance to your problem:** The commutation concept is directly applicable. If you have the agent's hunks and want to know if they were \\\"consumed\\\" by a commit, you can test whether each agent hunk commutes with the commit's diff. Non-commuting means the commit touched the same region.\\n\\n**Source:** [tummychow/git-absorb](https://github.com/tummychow/git-absorb), specifically `src/commute.rs`\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2. git range-diff\\n\\n**How it works:** git range-diff matches corresponding commits between two versions of a patch series using a **bipartite graph assignment** algorithm.\\n\\n**Matching algorithm:**\\n1. Compute the diff (patch) for each commit in both ranges\\n2. For every pair of commits (one from each range), compute a \\\"diff of diffs\\\" -- the textual diff between the two patches\\n3. Use the size of each diff-of-diffs as the cost in a cost matrix\\n4. Add dummy nodes for wholly new/removed commits with a fudge-factor cost\\n5. Solve the **minimum-cost assignment** using the **Jonker-Volgenant algorithm** (cubic runtime)\\n\\n**Key insight:** It operates at commit granularity, not hunk granularity. It measures similarity between entire patches, not individual hunks.\\n\\n**Relevance to your problem:** The approach of \\\"diff two diffs and measure similarity\\\" is conceptually useful but heavyweight for your use case. The Jonker-Volgenant assignment is overkill when you have just two diffs to compare (agent diff vs commit diff) rather than two series of commits.\\n\\n**Source:** [git range-diff documentation](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-range-diff), [range-diff.c in git source](https://github.com/git/git/blob/master/range-diff.c)\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 3. Three-Way Merge / diff3\\n\\n**How diff3 works:**\\n1. Compute `diff(O, A)` and `diff(O, B)` where O is the common ancestor\\n2. Align matching regions across all three texts\\n3. Classify each chunk:\\n   - **Both unchanged:** Output the original\\n   - **Only A changed:** Output A's version (A's change)\\n   - **Only B changed:** Output B's version (B's change)\\n   - **Both changed differently:** Conflict\\n\\n**Change attribution:** diff3 inherently tells you which side a change came from. This is exactly the property you need: given base (pre-agent state), A (agent's version), and B (committed version), diff3 classification tells you which agent changes are present in B.\\n\\n**Go implementations:**\\n- [epiclabs-io/diff3](https://github.com/epiclabs-io/diff3) -- Go port of a JS implementation based on Synchrotron. Provides `Merge(a, o, b, detailed, labelA, labelB)` returning a `MergeResult`.\\n- [charlesvdv/go-three-way-merge](https://github.com/charlesvdv/go-three-way-merge) -- Another Go library for three-way merge.\\n- [golang/go#68765](https://github.com/golang/go/issues/68765) -- Ongoing discussion about adding diff3 to Go's standard tools.\\n\\n**Academic reference:** [\\\"A Formal Investigation of Diff3\\\"](https://www.cis.upenn.edu/~bcpierce/papers/diff3-short.pdf) by Khanna, Kuber, and Pierce (FSTTCS 2007) -- formal analysis of diff3 properties and guarantees about non-conflicting edits to well-separated regions.\\n\\n**Relevance to your problem:** This is highly applicable. With three versions (base, agent-version, committed-version), diff3 can classify every chunk as \\\"agent-only change,\\\" \\\"commit-only change,\\\" \\\"both changed identically\\\" (consumed), or \\\"conflict\\\" (modified differently). This directly answers \\\"which agent hunks were included in the commit.\\\"\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 4. Patch Algebra / Hunk Intersection\\n\\n**Darcs patch commutation:**\\nTwo hunk patches on the same file commute if their line ranges do not overlap. When they do commute, you adjust line offsets. When they overlap, you have a conflict (cannot commute). The formal rule from Darcs (Haskell):\\n- If `p1` occurs in an earlier part of the file than `p2`, they commute by adjusting line offsets\\n- If they overlap in line ranges, they do NOT commute -- this signals a dependency/conflict\\n\\n**Pijul's category-theoretic approach:**\\nMerge is defined as a **pushout** in a category where files are objects and patches are arrows. The key paper is [\\\"A Categorical Theory of Patches\\\"](https://arxiv.org/abs/1311.3903) by Mimram and Di Giusto. The core insight: the \\\"free completion under finite colimits\\\" of the file category gives you a system where every pair of patches has a well-defined merge (pushout), with conflicts represented as objects labeled by lines with ordering relations.\\n\\n**Homotopical Patch Theory** (Angiuli, Morehouse, Licata, Harper -- [CMU paper](https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~rwh/papers/htpt/jfp.pdf)): Models patch theory using higher inductive types in homotopy type theory, separating the formal theory from the repository interpretation.\\n\\n**Relevance to your problem:** Patch commutation from Darcs is the most directly applicable concept. The question \\\"did this commit consume this agent hunk?\\\" is equivalent to \\\"does this agent hunk commute with the commit's inverse?\\\" If not, the regions overlap and the hunk was (at least partially) consumed. The category-theoretic approaches are elegant but impractical to implement for your use case.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 5. Code Review Tools\\n\\n**Gerrit -- `GitPositionTransformer` and `CommentPorter`:**\\n\\nGerrit's ported-comments feature (introduced in 3.4) maps comment positions across patchsets using a two-phase algorithm:\\n\\n1. **File path resolution:** Handle renamed/deleted/copied files\\n2. **Line range shifting:** Process range mappings sequentially top-to-bottom, tracking cumulative line shifts. If a comment's position falls within a changed range, it uses a conflict strategy (either omit the position or degrade to file-level).\\n\\nKey classes: `GitPositionTransformer` (handles the position mapping), `CommentPorter` (orchestrates porting of unresolved comments across patchsets). The algorithm is essentially: walk through the diff hunks, maintaining a running offset, and adjust comment line numbers accordingly. Comments on changed lines get marked as conflicting/outdated.\\n\\n**GitHub:**\\nGitHub tracks which lines were modified between force-pushes. Comments on lines that changed in a subsequent push are marked \\\"outdated.\\\" The algorithm is simpler than Gerrit's -- if the line a comment was on is part of a changed hunk in the new push, it's outdated.\\n\\n**Gitea:**\\nUses `git blame` to track whether commented lines changed, automatically marking outdated comments. Has known issues with incorrect line number tracking after insertions.\\n\\n**Relevance to your problem:** Gerrit's `GitPositionTransformer` pattern (sequential range-mapping with cumulative offset tracking) is a practical, proven approach for mapping line positions across diffs. This is useful if you need to track \\\"where did this agent hunk end up after the commit.\\\"\\n\\n**Source:** [Gerrit source at googlesource.com](https://gerrit.googlesource.com/gerrit/)\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 6. Practical Approaches\\n\\nGiven the agent's diff (`base -> agent_version`) and a commit's diff (`parent -> commit`), here are the approaches ranked by simplicity and reliability:\\n\\n**Approach A: Three-way diff (RECOMMENDED)**\\n\\nThis is the simplest reliable algorithm:\\n\\n1. You have three versions of each file: `base` (before agent), `agent_version` (agent's changes), `committed_version` (what was actually committed)\\n2. Run diff3 with `base` as the ancestor, `agent_version` as side A, `committed_version` as side B\\n3. Classification:\\n   - Chunks where A changed but B matches base = **agent changes NOT committed** (remaining)\\n   - Chunks where B changed but A matches base = **user's own changes** (not from agent)\\n   - Chunks where both A and B changed identically = **agent changes COMMITTED** (consumed)\\n   - Chunks where both changed differently = **agent changes MODIFIED** by user (partially consumed)\\n\\nThis leverages diff3's inherent change-attribution. Go libraries: [epiclabs-io/diff3](https://github.com/epiclabs-io/diff3) or [charlesvdv/go-three-way-merge](https://github.com/charlesvdv/go-three-way-merge).\\n\\n**Approach B: Residual diff**\\n\\n1. Compute `diff(agent_version, committed_version)` -- this is the \\\"residual\\\"\\n2. If the residual is empty for a file, all agent changes were committed verbatim\\n3. If the residual contains hunks, analyze them against the original agent diff to determine which hunks remain\\n4. Limitation: Cannot distinguish \\\"user removed an agent change\\\" from \\\"user added their own change\\\" without the base version\\n\\n**Approach C: Reverse-apply check**\\n\\n1. For each hunk in the agent's diff, try `git apply --reverse --check` against the committed version\\n2. If reverse-apply succeeds for a hunk, that hunk was consumed (its changes are present)\\n3. If it fails, the hunk was not consumed or was modified\\n4. Limitation: Context-sensitive -- may fail due to surrounding changes even when the core change is present. Also requires shelling out to git per hunk, which is expensive.\\n\\n**Approach D: Hunk-level line-range overlap (simplest approximation)**\\n\\n1. Parse both diffs into hunks per file using [sourcegraph/go-diff](https://github.com/sourcegraph/go-diff) or [bluekeyes/go-gitdiff](https://github.com/bluekeyes/go-gitdiff)\\n2. For each agent hunk, check if the commit's diff has a hunk touching the same line range in the same file\\n3. If the commit hunk's added lines contain the agent hunk's added lines (substring/subsequence match), the agent hunk was consumed\\n4. Limitation: Fragile with split/reorganized hunks and line-offset shifts\\n\\n**Approach E: Commutation test (git-absorb style)**\\n\\n1. Parse the agent's diff and the commit's diff into hunks\\n2. For each agent hunk, test if it commutes with each commit hunk (using the algorithm from git-absorb's `commute.rs`)\\n3. Non-commuting means the commit touched the same region -- the agent hunk was likely consumed\\n4. To confirm consumption vs. conflict, compare the actual line content\\n5. Advantage: Well-founded in patch theory. Disadvantage: Requires implementing the commutation logic.\\n\\n**Recommendation:** Approach A (three-way diff) is the most reliable and semantically clean. You already have all three versions available (the checkpoint stores the base state, the agent produced its version, and the commit is the committed version). The diff3 algorithm gives you exactly the classification you need, with proven Go libraries available. It handles edge cases like line reordering and partial hunk inclusion naturally.\\n\\nFor a quick-and-dirty first pass, Approach D (hunk overlap) combined with content matching gives a good approximation and is easy to implement with existing Go diff libraries.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Key Go Libraries for Implementation\\n\\n| Library | Purpose | Link |\\n|---------|---------|------|\\n| `sourcegraph/go-diff` | Unified diff parsing, `FileDiff`/`Hunk` structs | [pkg.go.dev](https://pkg.go.dev/sourcegraph.com/sourcegraph/go-diff/diff) |\\n| `bluekeyes/go-gitdiff` | Git diff parsing + patch application | [github.com](https://github.com/bluekeyes/go-gitdiff) |\\n| `epiclabs-io/diff3` | Three-way merge with conflict detection | [github.com](https://github.com/epiclabs-io/diff3) |\\n| `charlesvdv/go-three-way-merge` | Three-way merge on text | [github.com](https://github.com/charlesvdv/go-three-way-merge) |\\n| `go-git/go-git` | Git operations (already in your codebase) | [github.com](https://github.com/go-git/go-git) |\\n\\n### Key Academic Papers\\n\\n| Paper | Authors | Relevance |\\n|-------|---------|-----------|\\n| [A Formal Investigation of Diff3](https://www.cis.upenn.edu/~bcpierce/papers/diff3-short.pdf) | Khanna, Kuber, Pierce (2007) | Formal properties of diff3, guarantees about well-separated edits |\\n| [A Categorical Theory of Patches](https://arxiv.org/abs/1311.3903) | Mimram, Di Giusto (2013) | Merge as pushout, theoretical foundation for patch intersection |\\n| [Homotopical Patch Theory](https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~rwh/papers/htpt/jfp.pdf) | Angiuli, Morehouse, Licata, Harper (2014/2016) | Patch theory via higher inductive types |\\n| [Darcs Patch Theory](https://www.cs.tufts.edu/~nr/cs257/archive/david-roundy/Theory%20of%20patches.html) | Roundy | Original theory of patch commutation |\\n| [Ganesh Patch Algebra](https://darcs.net/Theory/GaneshPatchAlgebra) | Sittampalam et al. | Formal properties of patch commutation |\\n\\nSources:\\n- [tummychow/git-absorb](https://github.com/tummychow/git-absorb)\\n- [Super-charging git rebase with git absorb](https://andrewlock.net/super-charging-git-rebase-with-git-absorb/)\\n- [torbiak/git-autofixup](https://github.com/torbiak/git-autofixup)\\n- [Absorb changes across a topic branch](https://torbiak.com/post/autofixup/)\\n- [git range-diff documentation](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-range-diff)\\n- [git/range-diff.c source](https://github.com/git/git/blob/master/range-diff.c)\\n- [diff3 Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diff3)\\n- [Merging with diff3 - The If Works](https://blog.jcoglan.com/2017/05/08/merging-with-diff3/)\\n- [epiclabs-io/diff3 (Go)](https://github.com/epiclabs-io/diff3)\\n- [charlesvdv/go-three-way-merge (Go)](https://github.com/charlesvdv/go-three-way-merge)\\n- [golang/go#68765 - three-way merge](https://github.com/golang/go/issues/68765)\\n- [Understanding Darcs/Patch theory](https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Understanding_Darcs/Patch_theory)\\n- [Darcs Patch Algebra](https://darcs.net/Theory/GaneshPatchAlgebra)\\n- [Pijul Model](https://pijul.org/model/)\\n- [Part 1: Merging and patches](https://jneem.github.io/merging/)\\n- [Gerrit 3.4.x release notes](https://www.gerritcodereview.com/3.4.html)\\n- [Gerrit Review UI](https://gerrit-review.googlesource.com/Documentation/user-review-ui.html)\\n- [GitHub PR commenting docs](https://docs.github.com/en/pull-requests/collaborating-with-pull-requests/reviewing-changes-in-pull-requests/commenting-on-a-pull-request)\\n- [sourcegraph/go-diff](https://github.com/sourcegraph/go-diff)\\n- [bluekeyes/go-gitdiff](https://github.com/bluekeyes/go-gitdiff)\\n- [git-apply documentation](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-apply)\\n- [A Formal Investigation of Diff3](https://www.cis.upenn.edu/~bcpierce/papers/diff3-short.pdf)\\n- [A Categorical Theory of Patches](https://arxiv.org/abs/1311.3903)\\n- [Homotopical Patch Theory](https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~rwh/papers/htpt/jfp.pdf)</result>\\n<usage><total_tokens>49177</total_tokens><tool_uses>49</tool_uses><duration_ms>336310</duration_ms></usage>\\n</task-notification>\\nFull transcript available at: /tmp/claude-1000/-Users-soph-Work-entire-devenv-cli/tasks/a3a852a2c8fa36ec5.output\"},\"uuid\":\"3c75ff76-8d70-4526-b0d5-af8af6b5d7f6\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:48:52.802Z\",\"permissionMode\":\"bypassPermissions\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"3c75ff76-8d70-4526-b0d5-af8af6b5d7f6\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_0156PrxUzbNLQKST87qrj4nA\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"All three agents are back. Let me synthesize the key findings and update the spec.\\n\\nThe standout finding is the **three-way diff (diff3) approach**. It's the cleanest algorithm for hunk consumption detection:\\n\\nGiven three versions of a file:\\n- **O** (base/origin) — before the agent touched it\\n- **A** (agent version) — what the agent wrote\\n- **B** (committed version) — what the user actually committed\\n\\ndiff3 classifies every chunk:\\n\\n| O→A | O→B | Meaning |\\n|-----|-----|---------|\\n| unchanged | unchanged | Neither touched it |\\n| **changed** | unchanged | **Agent change NOT committed** (remaining) |\\n| unchanged | **changed** | User's own edit (not from agent) |\\n| **changed identically** | **changed identically** | **Agent change COMMITTED** (consumed) |\\n| **changed differently** | **changed differently** | Agent change modified by user (partially consumed) |\\n\\nThis is exactly the classification we need. And we already have all three versions available:\\n- **O**: the base commit (stored in `state.BaseCommit` / `state.AttributionBaseCommit`)\\n- **A**: the agent's file blob (stored in shadow branch during session, needs to be preserved via carry-forward ref)\\n- **B**: the committed file (always available in HEAD)\\n\\nThe other key findings:\\n\\n- **git-absorb's commutation algorithm** is an alternative — tests if two hunks can be reordered. Non-commuting means they touch the same region. Simpler but less precise than diff3.\\n- **Go libraries exist**: `epiclabs-io/diff3` for three-way merge, `bluekeyes/go-gitdiff` for diff parsing, `sourcegraph/go-diff` for unified diff parsing. Plus go-git's built-in `DiffTree()` → `Patch()` pipeline.\\n- **`refs/entire/carry_forward`** works perfectly with go-git — not pushed, not fetched, keeps objects reachable, invisible in `git branch`.\\n- **Performance budget**: ~30-50ms for hunk parsing on typical files, well within the <200ms hook budget.\\n\\nLet me update the spec with the consolidated design.\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":4934,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":136416,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":4934},\"output_tokens\":1,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYkfpvQvws3enUqM1yeru\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"e28fd256-a8e2-4fb4-957d-8641008c6c48\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:49:09.024Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"e28fd256-a8e2-4fb4-957d-8641008c6c48\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.6