 new changes, as soon as it does, we wipe the old shadow branch and put all local changes in to a new shadow branch, in the example that would mean 100-120 might be associated to the new session but so be it\"},\"uuid\":\"617d8390-6ce0-41b9-820a-ffbb1e0c54e2\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T21:50:55.013Z\",\"permissionMode\":\"bypassPermissions\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"617d8390-6ce0-41b9-820a-ffbb1e0c54e2\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01BQdN7EfVsoFwshupbkdJQF\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"This is a really interesting simplification. Let me think through this carefully.\\n\\nThe idea is:\\n1. Session 1 makes changes to lines 20-50 and 100-120\\n2. User commits lines 20-50 → shadow branch updated to only contain 100-120\\n3. If user commits 100-120 next → carry-forward complete, session 1 done\\n4. BUT if a NEW session starts and makes file changes → wipe the old shadow branch, start fresh\\n5. The uncommitted lines 100-120 from session 1 would be attributed to session 2 (or whatever session is now active)\\n\\n\\n6. This means the shadow branch only ever belongs to the current active session, and when a new session produces changes, the old carry-forward gets abandoned entirely. Once a new session starts working, the previous session can be fully marked as ended and cleaned up without needing to track lingering references.\\n\\nThe main tradeoff here is that lines from an earlier session might get attributed to a later one if they're carried forward and then committed, which isn't strictly accurate but doesn't matter much in practice since the user is doing the committing anyway. The shadow branch still needs to exist during carry-forward, but only until the next session starts, which keeps the implementation much simpler overall.\\n\\nMost users won't leave uncommitted changes sitting around for days without starting a new session—the typical pattern is work, commit some changes, then start fresh. So when a new session begins, I can check for existing carry-forward from other sessions, wipe the old shadow branch, and let the new session take over all uncommitted changes, fully cleaning up the old session state.\\n\\nFor implementation, I'd check in `initializeSession` or `HandleTurnStart` for existing carry-forward, reset the shadow branch to start fresh with current working tree changes, and mark old sessions as fully condensed. The new session's first SaveStep captures the full working tree state including any leftover changes from the previous session.\\n\\nThis is much simpler than diff3 and properly handles the shadow branch as a staging area that resets when a new session starts. The carry-forward mechanism already handles updating the shadow branch to reflect only what remains in the working tree after a partial commit, so the shadow branch naturally stays in sync with the current state. between the new HEAD and the shadow branch tree would show only 100-120. So the implicit diff works.\\n\\nBut actually... the carry-forward shadow branch is built by `buildTreeWithChanges` which takes the new HEAD tree and overlays the working tree versions of remaining files. So the shadow tree = new HEAD + working tree versions. The working tree still has lines 100-120 changed (uncommitted). So `diff(new HEAD, shadow)` = lines 100-120. This is correct.\\n\\nWhen a new session starts, the new session's first SaveStep also captures the working tree. If the working tree still has lines 100-120 from the old session plus new changes from the new session, all of that goes into the new shadow branch. The old shadow branch can be deleted.\\n\\nThis is actually really clean. Let me think about what needs to change: when a new session starts and there are ENDED sessions with carry-forward, those sessions get marked FullyCondensed and their shadow branches get deleted. The new session's first SaveStep captures the full working tree state including any leftover changes from old sessions, which already happens with `IsFirstCheckpoint: true` in `WriteTemporary`. Lines 100-120 get attributed to the new session, which is an acceptable tradeoff.\\n\\nThe simplification is elegant: no `refs/entire/carry_forward` needed, no diff3 needed, no new libraries needed. Shadow branches still get used but with a shorter lifecycle, and ENDED sessions get cleaned up deterministically when the next session starts instead of relying on time-based cleanup. This is a much better first step than the diff3 approach, which could always be added later if more precise attribution becomes necessary.\\n\\nNow I'm thinking through the edge case where the user never starts a new session but keeps making split commits. In that case, the carry-forward still works as it does today — the shadow branch persists, file-level comparison happens, and eventual cleanup happens via stale detection. This is unchanged from the existing behavior.\\n\\nThe real improvement is for the common case where a new session starts before all carry-forward is consumed. But I need to be more careful about the trigger here. The user's proposal says to wipe the old shadow branch and put all local changes into a new shadow branch \\\"as soon as\\\" the new session generates file changes. So it's not just about a new session starting, but about the new session actually modifying files. When the new session does its first SaveStep, that's when all the local changes get captured in the new shadow branch.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":482,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":148881,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":482},\"