ession_id\\\", sessionID))\\n\\treturn nil\\n}\\n\\n// calculatePromptAttributionAtStart calculates attribution at prompt start (before agent runs).\\n// This captures user changes since the last checkpoint - no filtering needed since\\n// the agent hasn't made any changes yet.\\n//\",\"numLines\":120,\"startLine\":1700,\"totalLines\":2315}},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"4dd7fe9e-e86b-48b6-9e3a-9581bd19d436\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"feceab5d-ef5e-4a7b-b671-4470dd3df0a4\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9b854080-5799-41cb-91c1-a3714b4bb75f\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"wild-soaring-treasure\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01Nd7YJCJkZCVTXJD2aBr5Uo\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Good. Now I see the full picture. Here's my analysis:\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Yes, this works and dramatically simplifies things.** Here's why:\\n\\n### What changes\\n\\nThe only real change is: **when a new session's first `SaveStep` runs (`StepCount == 0`), clean up ENDED sessions with carry-forward on the same worktree.**\\n\\n`WriteTemporary` with `IsFirstCheckpoint: true` already calls `collectChangedFiles()` which runs `git status --porcelain -z` — this captures everything dirty in the working tree, including leftover agent changes from old sessions. The new shadow branch naturally absorbs those changes.\\n\\n### What this means for the lifecycle\\n\\n| Scenario | Today | Proposed |\\n|----------|-------|----------|\\n| Session ends, user commits all files | Shadow branch deleted in PostCommit | Same |\\n| Session ends, user splits commits | Shadow branch persists for carry-forward until all committed or 7-day timeout | Same within the session, but cleared on next session start |\\n| Session ends, new session starts + does work | Old shadow branch lingers until 7 days or next commit with overlap | Old session cleaned up on new session's first SaveStep |\\n| Session ends, user never commits remaining | Lingers 7 days | Same (no new session to take over) |\\n\\n### What it simplifies\\n\\n1. **No diff3 needed** — file-level comparison as today\\n2. **No new ref namespace** — shadow branches work as-is\\n3. **No new libraries** — pure control flow change\\n4. **Deterministic cleanup** — ENDED sessions with carry-forward are cleaned up the moment a new session produces work, not on a 7-day timer\\n5. **Attribution is \\\"good enough\\\"** — leftover lines get attributed to the new session. The user made a conscious choice to start a new session without committing, so this is a reasonable default.\\n\\n### Implementation\\n\\nThe change is small — roughly:\\n\\n1. In `SaveStep` (or `InitializeSession`), when creating the first checkpoint for a new session, find ENDED sessions on the same worktree with `FilesTouched > 0`\\n2. Mark them `FullyCondensed = true`\\n3. Delete their shadow branches\\n4. The new session's `IsFirstCheckpoint: true` already captures the full working tree\\n\\nThe carry-forward shadow branch code (`carryForwardToNewShadowBranch`, `filesWithRemainingAgentChanges`) stays exactly as-is for the **within-session** split commit case (ACTIVE session, multiple commits during one turn). It only goes away for **cross-session** carry-forward.\\n\\n### The tradeoff is clearly stated\\n\\nLines 100-120 from Session 1 get attributed to Session 2. This is documented behavior, not a bug. The user chose to start a new session without committing. The checkpoint for commit 1 (lines 20-50) still correctly belongs to Session 1.\\n\\n---\\n\\nShould I add this as an \\\"Option B: Session-Bounded Carry-Forward\\\" to the spec alongside the diff3 approach? It could be Phase 1 (simpler, ship sooner) with diff3 as a potential Phase 2 if more precise cross-session attribution is ever needed.\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"ca